node.text:
On this episode of AD Visits, sartorial sensation Eva Chen (@evachen212) invites us inside her Connecticut home designed by local firm @hendrickschurchill. See her many reading nooks, her @instagram-worthy kitchen, and more. Cover photo by @chrismottalini; styled by Dorcia Kelly.

Visit our link in bio to read more about her home.

node.text: We're back with another episode of AD Visits, and today, we're taking you to Hudson Yards to see the home of fashion designer @brian_atwood and husband @drjakedeutsch. With photography on every wall and incredible city views 64 stories above Manhattan, explore their high-rise artistic aerie. Cover photo by @twilliamsphoto.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 19, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
“It’s like a postcard,” says Hugo Sauzay, one half of the Parisian design duo @festenarchitecture, describing @belmondsplendidomare, the beloved Belmond hotel in Portofino. “You’re on a pier in Italy, you close your eyes, people are shouting, waves are crashing.” That was a feeling he and Charlotte de Tonnac, his partner in business and life, embraced when updating the iconic property, situated in a 1930s building with just 14 guest rooms. 

Step inside this hotel's magnificent design at our bio link. Photo by @mattiaaquilaphotography; design by @festenarchitecture

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 18, 2021. May be an image of furniture and kitchen.

node.text:
Drawing inspiration from two of his favorite places, Palm Springs and New Orleans (where he grew up), architect and designer @eddiemaestri created an atmosphere for his Dallas home that is both clean-lined and exuberant. In the kitchen, for example, he fashioned an island out of a bright yellow console with arched legs, topping it with a marble slab shaped like a surfboard. The floors were covered in geometrically patterned porcelain tiles, and the walls feature a bold wallpaper printed with lemon and seafoam circles.

Visit our bio link to explore the whole home. Photo by @nathanschroderphoto; styled by @jennyoconnorstudio; design by @maestristudio; words by @whatpaolasees.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 18, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
“We wanted the rooms to feel comfortable and not precious,” notes designer Edel Legaspi (@legaspicourtsdesign) about this Atherton home for client Brigette Lau. “The furniture selections ranged from organic, sculptural pieces to clean, modernist forms, all layered with soft textures and jewel-toned colors.” As for each piece of art on display, Lau chimes in: “You want it to complement and you want it to have its own personality.” Striking a similar note, Legaspi adds, “You don’t want everything to be a showstopper. I want someone to walk in and think, this is Brigette’s house.”

Tour the color-filled home at our bio link. Photo by @rogerdaviesphotography; design by @legaspicourtsdesign; words by @zoesessums.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 18, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
For @biscuithome founder and hospitality entrepreneur Bailey McCarthy (@baileyquin), a historic 1912 Chicago condo with a Parisian-inspired façade was love at first sight. The Gold Coast home-away-from-home, which is located inside a residential high-rise designed by famed classical architect Benjamin Howard Marshall, did however require a full gut renovation.

See the transformed home at our bio link. Photo by @aimeemazzenga; styling by @cate.ragan.styling and @darwin.fitz.design; design by @baileyquin; words by @allisonpduncan.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 17, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
To furnish her eclectic home, model @jesshart and designer Carlos Mota (@casamotachic) gravitated toward vintage pieces, which they mostly hit upon by combing through online auctions and boutiques. Some of Hart’s favorite finds from her New York apartment even made their way into the mix, like a suite of wicker armchairs and a black Herman Miller bench.

Tour her home from our latest issue at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; design by @casamotachic; words by @carly_olson.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 17, 2021. May be an image of living room and outdoors.

node.text:
If you ask Angelenos, Los Angeles has it all—beaches, mountains, deserts, farms, and cities. But that doesn’t mean a change of scenery isn’t necessary from time to time. This summer, a slew of new and beloved hotels beckons from Sonoma down to San Diego, with distinctive—and inspiring—atmospheres scattered liberally in between. Road trip, staycation, vacation: Whatever you care to call it, an escape from L.A. is an essential part of life in the great state of California.

Discover 10 alluring choices at our bio link. Photo courtesy of @thesurfridermalibu; words by @katromeyn.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 17, 2021. May be an image of living room.

node.text:
Architect and designer @eddiemaestri lives in a neighborhood of spacious modernist homes, many of them perched on a bucolic lake where geese, ducks, and turtles roam free. It doesn’t really feel like Dallas, and that’s partly why he fell in love with it. “I went on Trulia and typed ‘mid-century’ and ‘waterfront,’ not expecting to find anything, and then our house popped up,” he says. “I had never heard of this little pocket of Dallas and I was immediately obsessed. We had been looking for the right home for years.”

Visit our bio link to explore the whole home. Photo by @nathanschroderphoto; styled by @jennyoconnorstudio; design by @maestristudio; words by @whatpaolasees.

node.text:
On this episode of AD Visits, sartorial sensation Eva Chen (@evachen212) invites us inside her Connecticut home designed by local firm @hendrickschurchill. See her many reading nooks, her @instagram-worthy kitchen, and more. Cover photo by @chrismottalini; styled by Dorcia Kelly.

Visit our link in bio to read more about her home.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 16, 2021. May be an image of table, chandelier and living room.

node.text:
“Art to me is not about having a wall to fill,” says designer and owner of this Seattle home, Brian Paquette (@brian.paquette_), who studied conceptual art and painting. “I buy it because I have an [eternal] connection to it, like you just seemingly can’t live without it. You feel like it’s a ghost limb that you didn’t know you had.” Paquette is drawn to the work of Seattle artist @lakshmimuirhead, and one of her abstract paintings hangs on the wall of the dining room. On Seattle’s signature gray days, a chandelier from New York’s @apparatusstudio, which is made of glass orbs, fills this space with warm light.

Tour every space at our bio link. Photo by @aaronleitz; design by @brian.paquette_; words by Jennifer Flowers.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 16, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
“He saw the built environment as a way to connect people and lives,” notes Stuart Graff, president and CEO of the Frank Lloyd Wright Foundation (@wrighttaliesin). Today the organization is looking to the past and future, endeavoring to, as Graff explains, “present Wright in ways that encourage people to take his ideas and act on them.”

Learn more about the future of Wright's Taliesin at our bio link. Photo by John Miller and Hedrich Blessing; words by @samuelcochran.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 15, 2021. May be an image of furniture and bedroom.

node.text:
For the interiors of this home on Lake Austin, designer Emily Seiders (@studioseiders) took cues from the clients’ personalities and stories about their travels (“they loved Soho Farmhouse in Oxfordshire and enjoy spending time in Manhattan”) in order to come up with a design that’s easy yet refined with just a touch of whimsy. “We were not chasing trends, and that’s something hard to do in this digital age,” says Seiders. “I wanted to create a home that’s livable but very special, with a whole lot of attention to detail.”

Explore every space at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; design by @ryanstreetarchitects and @studioseiders; words by @whatpaolasees.

Designs of this Monaco duplex were commissioned to complement the clients' art collection. “We are most proud of the balance between our interior design and their collection,” architect @emilhumbert says of a light fixture by the @bouroullecbrothers. “Everything works together…. The challenge was to make the place [feel] full of life within this modern building.” Sitting atop a 1950s Brazilian cabinet by Martin Eisler and Carlo Hauner are ceramic pieces by French artist Georges Jouve, a sculpture by American artist Sherrie Levine, and a 19th-century Venetian vase. The Jean Prouvé armchair is complemented by work by @theastergates and a painting by South African artist @cinga_samson.
